00:12:33,625 --> 00:12:36,416
Ashoka's conversion showed Buddhism could transform

285
00:12:36,416 --> 00:12:38,125
even the most violent ruler

286
00:12:38,500 --> 00:12:40,833
but can a philosophy spread across continents

287
00:12:40,833 --> 00:12:42,541
without armies carrying it

288
00:12:42,916 --> 00:12:44,791
the answer lies in how Buddhism traveled

289
00:12:44,791 --> 00:12:46,416
the ancient highways of commerce

290
00:12:51,291 --> 00:12:53,166
while many religions followed the sword

291
00:12:53,666 --> 00:12:55,791
Buddhism followed the merchant's caravan

292
00:12:56,208 --> 00:12:58,750
trade routes became Buddhism's superhighways

293
00:12:58,791 --> 00:13:01,875
especially the vast network we now call the Silk Road

294
00:13:02,041 --> 00:13:03,958
connecting China to Central Asia

295
00:13:03,958 --> 00:13:07,166
India the Middle East and eventually Europe

296
00:13:08,250 --> 00:13:09,666
let me take you to Dunhuang

297
00:13:09,666 --> 00:13:12,041
China around the year 600 CE

298
00:13:13,541 --> 00:13:16,000
a weary merchant caravan arrives at the oasis

299
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:18,416
after weeks crossing the Taklamakan Desert

300
00:13:18,750 --> 00:13:21,000
their camels laden with silk and spices

301
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:24,583
destined for Persia the desert crossing has been brutal

302
00:13:24,833 --> 00:13:25,666
sandstorms

303
00:13:25,666 --> 00:13:28,791
bandits and the constant threat of death by thirst

304
00:13:29,375 --> 00:13:30,958
but here at the edge of China

305
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:32,833
something remarkable greets them

306
00:13:33,125 --> 00:13:35,875
a complex of caves carved into cliff faces

307
00:13:36,625 --> 00:13:37,458
inside

308
00:13:37,541 --> 00:13:40,500
magnificent Buddha statues reach toward the ceiling

309
00:13:40,583 --> 00:13:42,500
walls covered in vibrant paintings

310
00:13:42,500 --> 00:13:44,083
depicting the Buddha's life

311
00:13:44,625 --> 00:13:46,541
the travelers find not just shelter

312
00:13:46,541 --> 00:13:48,458
but a place to deposit valuables

313
00:13:48,583 --> 00:13:51,750
exchange currency receive medical care

314
00:13:51,916 --> 00:13:53,291
and restore their spirits

315
00:13:53,291 --> 00:13:55,125
before the next leg of their journey

316
00:13:56,333 --> 00:13:58,416
a local monk approaches the lead merchant

317
00:13:58,416 --> 00:14:01,541
offering tea they share no common language

318
00:14:01,541 --> 00:14:02,916
yet through translation

319
00:14:02,958 --> 00:14:05,166
the merchant hears teachings that make sense to him

320
00:14:05,166 --> 00:14:07,291
regardless of his culture or background

321
00:14:07,916 --> 00:14:10,666
the focus on ethical business practices

322
00:14:10,791 --> 00:14:13,958
on reducing suffering on finding inner peace

323
00:14:13,958 --> 00:14:15,875
amid the chaos of desert crossings

324
00:14:16,708 --> 00:14:18,958
this speaks to his daily reality

325
00:14:20,125 --> 00:14:21,916
before departing the merchant leaves

326
00:14:21,916 --> 00:14:24,750
a generous donation to expand the cave complex

327
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:27,875
ensuring future travelers will find the same refuge

328
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:30,833
scenes like this played out again and again

329
00:14:30,833 --> 00:14:32,291
across Asia's trade routes

330
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:35,000
as historian Jerry Bentley noted

331
00:14:35,250 --> 00:14:36,791
Buddhism traveled the Silk Roads

332
00:14:36,791 --> 00:14:39,000
in the wallets and saddle bags of merchants

333
00:14:39,041 --> 00:14:40,708
not on the backs of warriors

334
00:14:41,458 --> 00:14:43,166
Buddhism offered practical benefits

335
00:14:43,166 --> 00:14:46,541
for traveling merchants its emphasis on ethical conduct

336
00:14:46,541 --> 00:14:48,750
created trust between trading partners

337
00:14:49,125 --> 00:14:52,208
its monastery networks provided safe places to rest

338
00:14:52,500 --> 00:14:54,916
store goods and exchange currency

339
00:14:55,541 --> 00:14:56,833
and its universal principles

340
00:14:56,833 --> 00:14:58,083
worked across different cultures

341
00:14:58,083 --> 00:14:59,000
and languages

342
00:14:59,625 --> 00:15:02,166
Buddhism also excelled at cultural adaptation

343
00:15:02,458 --> 00:15:05,250
unlike religions that demanded exclusive allegiance

344
00:15:06,041 --> 00:15:08,166
Buddhism allowed practitioners to maintain

345
00:15:08,166 --> 00:15:10,750
local customs alongside Buddhist practice

346
00:15:11,875 --> 00:15:13,708
the Buddhist concept of upaya

347
00:15:13,708 --> 00:15:16,958
or skillful means gave missionaries flexibility

348
00:15:17,458 --> 00:15:19,375
they could present Buddhism differently

349
00:15:19,375 --> 00:15:20,708
depending on the audience

350
00:15:21,041 --> 00:15:24,000
emphasizing philosophical aspects for the educated

351
00:15:24,500 --> 00:15:26,791
meditation for the spiritually inclined

352
00:15:27,125 --> 00:15:28,958
ethical teachings for rulers

353
00:15:29,250 --> 00:15:31,875
and devotional practices for common people

354
00:15:33,041 --> 00:15:34,958
Buddhism's journey along trade routes

355
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:37,916
demonstrates how ideas can spread without conquest

356
00:15:38,250 --> 00:15:39,916
but what happened when those ideas

357
00:15:39,916 --> 00:15:41,750
encountered established religions

358
00:15:41,875 --> 00:15:44,000
and deeply rooted belief systems

359
00:15:44,750 --> 00:15:46,333
the story of these encounters

360
00:15:46,333 --> 00:15:48,666
reveals Buddhism's unique flexibility

361
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:55,916
when Buddhism encountered other belief systems

362
00:15:55,916 --> 00:15:58,750
it typically sought harmony rather than conflict

363
00:15:59,333 --> 00:16:01,458
but the outcomes varied dramatically

364
00:16:02,208 --> 00:16:04,833
Buddhism's encounter with Islam proved more complex

365
00:16:04,833 --> 00:16:07,583
and sometimes tragic Arab armies

366
00:16:07,583 --> 00:16:08,708
conquering Central Asia

367
00:16:08,708 --> 00:16:10,416
in the 7th and 8th centuries

368
00:16:10,541 --> 00:16:12,916
encountered flourishing Buddhist civilizations

369
00:16:13,375 --> 00:16:16,333
monasteries crumbled libraries burned

370
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:19,708
the magnificent Bamiyan Buddhas in Afghanistan

371
00:16:19,708 --> 00:16:22,541
destroyed by the Taliban in 2001

372
00:16:22,541 --> 00:16:25,666
were first damaged during these early Muslim conquests

373
00:16:27,125 --> 00:16:29,500
why did Buddhism disappear from these regions

374
00:16:29,791 --> 00:16:32,375
not because Buddhists fought and lost holy wars

375
00:16:32,500 --> 00:16:34,250
but because Buddhist institutions

376
00:16:34,250 --> 00:16:36,333
couldn't survive without royal patronage

377
00:16:36,750 --> 00:16:38,041
the new Islamic rulers

378
00:16:38,041 --> 00:16:39,708
naturally favored their own faith

379
00:16:40,708 --> 00:16:42,208
throughout Southeast Asia

380
00:16:42,208 --> 00:16:43,916
a different story unfolded

381
00:16:43,916 --> 00:16:46,333
when Buddhism met indigenous animist traditions

382
00:16:46,333 --> 00:16:49,333
and Hinduism remarkable synthesis occurred

383
00:16:49,625 --> 00:16:52,666
Thai monks perform ceremonies honoring local spirits

384
00:16:53,833 --> 00:16:58,000
in Myanmar Nat worship continues alongside Buddhism

385
00:16:58,541 --> 00:17:00,833
on islands like Java and Bali

386
00:17:01,125 --> 00:17:04,000
Hindu and Buddhist elements blend seamlessly

387
00:17:04,708 --> 00:17:08,583
in China Buddhism encountered Confucianism and Taoism

388
00:17:08,958 --> 00:17:11,500
two sophisticated philosophical systems

389
00:17:11,500 --> 00:17:13,583
deeply embedded in Chinese culture

390
00:17:14,250 --> 00:17:16,500
Buddhist missionaries responded not with force

391
00:17:16,500 --> 00:17:18,083
but with skilled translation

392
00:17:18,583 --> 00:17:21,625
they used Taoist terms to explain Buddhist concepts

393
00:17:21,833 --> 00:17:23,666
making ideas like emptiness

394
00:17:23,875 --> 00:17:24,833
sunyata

395
00:17:25,041 --> 00:17:27,958
accessible through comparison with Taoist non action

396
00:17:27,958 --> 00:17:28,750
Wu Wei

397
00:17:29,958 --> 00:17:32,833
the result was a fascinating philosophical dialogue

398
00:17:33,125 --> 00:17:35,250
Buddhism influenced Chinese thought

399
00:17:35,416 --> 00:17:37,416
while being transformed into distinctively

400
00:17:37,416 --> 00:17:39,708
Chinese schools like Chan Zen

401
00:17:41,916 --> 00:17:43,250
Buddhism's journey to the west

402
00:17:43,250 --> 00:17:45,458
represents another fascinating chapter

403
00:17:45,958 --> 00:17:47,791
when Buddhist texts first reached Europe

404
00:17:47,791 --> 00:17:50,666
in the 19th century they influenced philosophers

405
00:17:50,666 --> 00:17:52,500
like Schopenhauer and Nietzsche

406
00:17:52,958 --> 00:17:55,000
unlike earlier religious encounters

407
00:17:55,125 --> 00:17:56,833
Buddhism entered western consciousness

408
00:17:56,833 --> 00:18:00,125
primarily as philosophy rather than competing religion

409
00:18:00,875 --> 00:18:03,916
in the 20th century figures like Alan Watts

410
00:18:03,916 --> 00:18:05,041
DT Suzuki

